## Web Research Complete

**Queries**: 5 searches executed
**Sources**: 7 relevant sources found
**Artifact**: `/home/asiri/.archon/workspaces/alexsiri7/reli/artifacts/runs/602a8e8a4196c7d3749d44ab68164c26/web-research.md`

### Key Findings

- **Root cause confirmed**: `RAILWAY_TOKEN` expired — this is the 4th recurrence (#733, #739, #742, #755). The "Validate Railway secrets" step calls the Railway GraphQL API and receives `Not Authorized`.
- **Fix is human-only**: Railway tokens are dashboard-issued static credentials. Agents cannot rotate them. The operator must go to `https://railway.com/account/tokens`, create a new token with **No expiration** (critical — the default TTL is likely short), and update the GitHub secret via `gh secret set RAILWAY_TOKEN --repo alexsiri7/reli`.
- **Runbook already exists**: `docs/RAILWAY_TOKEN_ROTATION_742.md` has the complete step-by-step. Once the new token is set, re-run the failed CI job `25022304652`.
- **Weekly health check timing**: The check runs Mondays; the failure hit on a Sunday — the token expired inside the check window. The machinery works; the human rotation step is the recurring bottleneck.
- **Railway does not support OIDC**: No short-lived, auto-rotating credential option exists for Railway as of April 2026 — static tokens with "No expiration" remain the best available approach.

### Gaps

- Railway's public docs don't show the "No expiration" UI option explicitly (it exists in the dashboard but is undocumented)
- Whether previous rotations accidentally used a short-TTL token (vs. a true no-expiry token) is unknown
